Wedding Pro Tip: 

Think about your getting ready location not just terms of proximity to the venue or convenience. Think about your photos as well!

Does the hotel have awful colors on the walls? Is the decor something you’d want to be photographed in? Is the room super dark or is there plenty of beautiful natural light?

Being aware of how these things affect your photos can make the difference between loving your getting ready photos and not so it’s definitely worth thinking about!

Wedding Pro Tip:

Want more time on your wedding day to spend with guests? Consider a pre or post wedding session with your partner! 

Everyone wants beautiful portraits from their wedding day, but sometimes scheduling or weather can limit the amount of time we can dedicate to those portraits. Moving your portraits to a separate day means you have plenty of extra time to enjoy on the wedding day plus a totally stress free portrait session without any of the wedding day hustle!

Definitely something to consider, especially for weddings with tighter timelines!

One of the most common questions I’m asked is what clients should wear for their engagement session. While I don’t have a one size fits all solution for everyone, I’ve got some tips that will hopefully help point you in the right direction:

- Make sure you’re comfortable. That means breaking in your heels before hand. I know they look amazing now and you don’t want to mess them up, but nobody wants blisters on their heels while trying to take cute photos.

- I’d lean towards a more formal look, or have an outfit change that has both a formal and casual look. That said, guys, we can do better than cargo shorts. Keep it business casual. 

- While we’re on the subject, guys, get a custom suit made. A well tailored blue suit never goes out of style and you’ll look amazing. There are a ton of options out there, but @stateandliberty made mine for an extremely reasonable price and without any exaggeration it’s one of the most comfortable pieces of clothing I own. Just do it, it’s totally worth it.

- Aim for complementary colors, not matching. We’ve all seen family beach photos with everyone in matching khaki shorts and white shirts. You don’t want that. 

- Finally, and this might be a bit contentious, maybe avoid white. I know it’s tempting, but remember, you’ll have a million photos of you wearing white on your wedding day. Shake things up a bit and wear something that speaks to your personal style.

I know there are a ton of options, but with a few basic rules it’s easy to look amazing for your engagement session. 

Do you have any other tips and tricks? I’d love to hear them!

Botany Bay is one of those places that seems like it shouldn’t exist. It’s an almost completely deserted 4500 acre property with a mix of just about everything you could want out of Charleston. From a gorgeous avenue of oaks, a beach filled with the remains of once huge trees that were swept into the ocean from coastal erosion and expansive marsh views, it’s pretty much a photographers dream.​​​​​​​​

Rakino Island, a tiny dot of land in the  Hauraki Gulf off the coast of New Zealand’s north island is something unbelievably special. 

It’s the kind of place that on a stormy day seems completely isolated from the rest of the world, even though you’re only a 45 minute ferry from the biggest city in New Zealand. It’s a place to disconnect and just exist.

I can’t really put into words how lucky I am to be able to visit regularly.

We interrupt your normally scheduled wedding content to bring you one of my favorite beaches in the world!

Piha and Muriwai beaches, along with most of the northern east coast of New Zealand were hit really hard by a recent typhoon and were either completely cut off from civilization or underwater (or both). It really wasn’t a great situation for anyone, especially given that it came 2 weeks after even more record flooding, but let’s hope that the NZ government has sorted out its recovery operation and gotten everyone well on the road to normalcy!

Happy 4th of July!

Can’t believe it’s been a year since these two were married at the absolutely beautiful Lake Genesis, WI!

Listening to the low rumble of avalanches echoing off of the valley walls isn’t the normal soundtrack for my sessions, but I’ll take it any day of the week. 

I’ve been digging through a series of bridal portraits that I did in New Zealand in late 2018 and while 90% are flash portraits that don’t really fit with my current work, there are some real gems to be had. Can’t wait to share more!

Finally, a massive shoutout to @cushlabeasley for waking up at 4:30am, hiking 4 miles and then changing into a wedding dress outside in the freezing cold. She’s a hero for this one!

Just realized this is my 4th photo in a row of the back of a couples head. Sorry about that. We’ll be back to faces tomorrow!

When people ask me why I shoot film, I’ll just show them this photo!

Back in August my wife, the extremely talented @cushlabeasley , gave me something of a challenge: commit to shooting film and make it a serious part of your workflow for at least a few weddings.

So I gave it a shot. (No pun intended) Armed with a newfound love of @kodakprofessional Gold 200, a Contax 645 and a wallet that was braced for impact, I burned through dozens of rolls over the course of the next few weeks.

To say that my jaw hit the floor when I received the scans back from @richardphotolab is hyperbolic, but only slightly. 

I fell in love instantly.

So over the next few months you’re going to start seeing a LOT more film work! I’m super excited for the fall season and I can’t wait to share more!

And with that it’s 2024!

The past year has been absolutely flat out. In addition to working with 48 incredible couples throughout the year, we also took on what became the monumental task of personally renovating our beautiful 1890’s home in Charleston.

What started as a 2-3 week job to strip paint off of a few windows quickly turned into the full restoration of all of the original heart pine trim, 6 windows, 2 fireplaces, an original glass transom and a gigantic set of pocket doors. 

It required learning a huge number of new skills, massive swings from frustration to elation and back again, some incredibly long days and ultimately 5 months of our time.

We hit some really low spots, and plans sometimes had to change but at the end of the day you keep going because you know it’ll all be worth it in the end. 

The good news though is that it was all worth it. All the added stress and all of the hours of work were finally wrapped up this week. It feels amazing and it’s reconfirmed just how much I love the home that @cushlabeasley and I have created. 

2023 was work. It was hard. But few things that are worth it are easy. In both my personal and professional life I created work that I am unbelievably proud of and I learned an incredible amount about what I’m capable of.

Professionally, 2024 is going to be all about picking up the proverbial ball and running with it. My commitment 6 months ago to shoot more film has only compounded my love of photography and shooting weddings and I’m genuinely giddy to think of what this year will bring. I can’t wait to share it with you.

Personally though it’ll about simplifying things, taking time to pursue hobbies that I don’t feel the need to attempt to monetize and generally just having more fun. 

So here’s to creating awesome work and having fun doing it! Happy New Year!
